<TEXT>
the ailing exxon valdez limped toward safe 
harbor today after postponing massive hull repairs for weeks while 
waiting offshore until environmental questions could be answered 
the tanker involved in the nations worst oil spill was 
scheduled to enter san diego bay early sunday under tow as it has 
been throughout the 2500mile journey south from alaska 
divers were confident they had cut off all the dangling steel 
plates torn loose during the southerly voyage and that the gutted 
tanker would be able to pass through the harbors shallows 
state environment officials said they would keep close watch on 
the lumbering ship when it enters the bay under escort surrounded 
by a flotilla of us coast guard boats 
local greenpeace activists said theyd be watching too 
following at a distance after staging a protest demonstration 
against exxon planned for sunday morning 
we are concerned that it will be discharging into the san 
diego bay said rick nadeau director of greenpeace in san diego 
if it does have some oil slicks coming out of it well be able 
to see that 
nadeau said greenpeace wants to see the valdez reach the dock 
safely because more environmental damage could occur if the tanker 
remains at sea any longer 
an 18mile oil slick was spotted near the tanker july 10 and 
since then the valdez has been halted about 55 miles off the coast 
of san diego 
numerous tests were conducted and the emergency platecutting 
work was undertaken exxon officials and state negotiators hammered 
out an agreement to allow valdez into port 
the valdez which spilled 11 million gallons of crude oil after 
slamming into a submerged reef in alaska was to execute a series 
of maneuvers simulating what it will have to do inside the harbor 
before being allowed into the bay 
exxon officials insist that periodict discharges from the valdez 
are nontoxic with barely detectable traces of oil state officials 
leery of exxon assurances have said the ship is releasing 
significant pollutants 
</TEXT>
