<TEXT>
two new hud audits say rent subsidies were 
improperly inflated by 6 million for two housing projects 
involving former agency officials 
the internal audits completed this month by the department of 
housing and urban developments inspector general found that local 
housing authorities in tulsa okla and gastonia nc allowed a 
mortgage company to establish the rents for the projects a 
violation of hud guidelines 
the tulsa project windsong apartments is owned by a 
partnership that includes four former hud officials philip winn 
lance wilson philip abrams and j michael queenan all four also 
had stakes in projects reviewed as part of a nationwide audit 
released in april that cited excessive rents as one of several 
problems afflicting the section 8 moderate rehabilitation program 
the gastonia development four seasons apartments is owned by a 
group that hired rhode islandbased consultant judith siegal to 
help obtain the lucrative rehabilitation subsidies 
ms siegal was among the lesserknown but more successful 
consultants cited in the earlier report which found that hud was 
being overcharged more than 400 million over the 15year life of 
the rehabilitation subsidies because of inflated rents 
the mortgage company that established the rents benton mortgage 
co of knoxville tenn also has figured prominently in an ongoing 
investigation of abuses at the agency the company coinsured the 
projects with hud 
all the audits noted that former hud officials had won a 
significant share of the rehabilitation money and that prominent 
republican consultants were successful in steering money to their 
clients 
since the report in april hud has been the subject of internal 
congressional and justice department investigations mismanagement 
and abuses have been found in a number of the multibilliondollar 
agencys programs 
hud secretary jack kemp suspended the moderate rehabilitation 
program the house in its budget bill for hud next year included 
no new funding for the program 
the two new audits obtained last week under the freedom of 
information act were not part of the nationwide review 
the audit of the tulsa project completed july 11 found that 
the tulsa housing authority misinterpreted hud guidelines and 
allowed benton to calculate the rents for the 202unit windsong 
complex 
as a result auditors said hud already had paid more than 
200000 in excess of what it should have since the subsidies began 
in 1987 and could overpay by as much as 34 million over the life 
of the contract unless the subsidies are reduced 
the findings of the gastonia audit completed july 24 were very 
similar 
investigators found that the gastonia housing authority allowed 
benton to set the rents which auditors said were calculated with a 
faulty formula and included ineligible costs as a result hud had 
paid 63000 in excessive subsidies from late 1987 through march 
and over the term of the contract will overpay rents by more than 
25 million unless the subsidies are recalculated 
in both the tulsa and gastonia audits hud urged the local 
housing officials and regional hud officials to recalculate the 
subsidies and to recover the overpaid amounts that process is just 
getting under way 
