<TEXT>
the selection of mieczyslaw f rakowski to 
lead polands communist party through an era of political upheaval 
culminates the remarkable comeback of a man ousted from government 
in 1985 
rakowski chosen saturday by a divided communist party only 
joined the partys ruling politburo on dec 15 1987 
although he supports a radical restructuring of the economy he 
acknowledges he is now linked more with the partys conservative 
elements than its reformist wing 
under rakowskis leadership as premier the government ended 
gasoline rationing and legalized the black market in foreign 
currencies 
but in his nine months as prime minister the economy has 
deteriorated and rakowski made little progress in winning the 
hearts of solidarity supporters who remember him as one of the 
unions scrappiest foes 
with inflation now in triple digits and many basic commodities 
such as meat bread and sugar in short supply rakowskis promotion 
to the head party post in a 17141 vote might seem peculiar 
he became deputy prime minister feb 12 1981 but his 
abrasiveness made him enemies he lost that post in november 1985 
when several hardliners were dumped from the government 
from 1985 to 1987 he held a largely ceremonial position as 
deputy speaker of the sejm or parliament 
he was one of 33 senior officials who ran unopposed for 
parliament in june but failed to capture even half the votes one 
party member in the debate saturday said only 35 percent of polish 
people voice confidence in the government now compared with 72 
percent shortly after rakowski took office 
but rakowskis calls for the party to stand firm in the face of 
its difficulties apparently have appealed to party conservatives 
and those in the central committee who feel threatened by the rise 
of solidaritys influence the union won 260 of 261 parliament 
seats it contested in june 
rakowski succeeds wojciech jaruzelski who resigned saturday as 
he had promised to do before being elected president 
a man of peasant origins who rose to become one of polands 
leading journalists from 1958 through 1982 rakowksi was editor of 
polityka a communistcontrolled but generally liberal weekly that 
was considered even daring through the 1970s 
the 62yearold rakowski was named prime minister sept 27 and 
formed his government oct 14 he was rebuffed by opposition 
members he sought to enlist 
although rakowski in january urged legalization of solidarity 
after its sevenyear ban he did not take an active role in the 
talks that followed solidarity was legalized again in april 
rakowski became unpopular with leaders of solidarity during its 
16month legal period in 198081 one of his first acts as prime 
minister was to announce the closing of the lenin shipyard in 
gdansk solidaritys birthplace in a move many union members 
interpreted as a personal vendetta 
during solidaritys early months as a legal group rakowski 
headed the governments committee for trade unions and served as 
the governments chief negotiator with solidarity 
he also played a major role in defending the suppression of the 
union after the introduction of martial law dec 13 1981 
born in the village of kowalewek in northwest poland on dec 1 
1926 rakowski was a teenage laborer during the nazi occupation of 
poland and served in the polish army from the time of the 
liberation until 1949 
he joined the communist party in 1946 and attended the institute 
of social sciences in moscow 
in a widely circulated memorandum on polands political 
situation written before his politburo appointment rakowski backed 
further democratization and economic reform 
but he also urged the party to stake out more clearly its 
ideological differences with solidarity 
in a newspaper interview last week rakowski said the party 
should resist attempts to divide it 
he called on the party to become a pragmatic leftist party of 
the 21st century but he added to be pragmatic does not mean 
to disrespect marxism and the historical achievements of polish 
socialists and communists 
