<TEXT>
prime minister mario machungo outlined 
the ruling partys new political and economic policies saturday and 
said an independent economy is necessary to build socialism 
the outline indicated that the party the front for the 
liberation of mozambique or frelimo is moving away from marxism 
and central planning 
frelimo has governed mozambique under a oneparty 
marxistleninist policy since gaining power after the country 
gained independence from portugal in 1975 
but its policy document presented last week to frelimos first 
national congress since 1983 dropped all references to marxism 
the document described the party as socialist it also said 
frelimo is open to all mozambicans and is not just a workerpeasant 
alliance 
the party congress has already been presented with its central 
committees recommendations to open ranks to businessmen property 
owners shopkeepers and religious believers 
the congress convened july 24 and is to close monday 
during saturdays session machungo said the process of 
building socialism requires the creation of an independent and 
advanced economy 
he said the effort also would require the active participation 
of various property regimes stateowned cooperative and peasant 
family property and private or jointventure forms of property 
several years ago the government began opening the economy 
encouraging private enterprise and foreign investments mainly to 
meet requirements for loans from the international monetary fund 
and world bank 
about half of mozambiques 14 million people are wholly or 
partly dependent on donated food and 16 million are refugees from 
the 12yearold civil war that has left hundreds of thousands dead 
machungo said the major change from the social and economic 
directives of 1983 is that today frelimo does not attempt to 
establish target figures for every sector of the economy instead 
the directives set out basic policy goals 
he said the new directives lay heavy stress on peasant family 
agriculture rather than on state farms but that state farms 
still have an important role in producing exports 
machungo said the directives also call for increased labor 
productivity and for the implementation of the principle of paying 
more to those who work more carry out their duties better and 
attain the best indexes of efficiency 
the central committee said it would allow private schools 
outlawed in 1975 to be reestablished because the government was 
unable to provide education for all of the countrys children it 
said rebels have destroyed or forced the closure of 2699 primary 
schools in rural areas 
</TEXT>
