underground bands she began working on raw like sushi last 
year 
music has always been natural to me she said but i 
didnt really make the decision to get involved with it until i was 
involved with working in a group 
musics always been there like a way of life always but i 
didnt start writing any material until i was out of two band 
situations i took everything i had learned from the rest of my 
life and did something with it 
buffalo stance combines rock jazz funk and disco 
the best blessing ive had in my life is feeling i dont have 
to define the various influences now were going to do a reggae 
song a jazz song in cat on a hot tin roof paul newmans 
saying i need the click in my head then ill feel all right 
at some point a few years ago i got that click its given 
me the freedom to make songs were in tune to where the raw energy 
is 
the next generation is a track off raw sushi neneh a 
mother of two is already thinking of a world far removed from the 
dance floors where her music is heard 
when you have a child all of life and all children begin to 
matter in a different way she said it opened me up children 
are not being given the right information and they need to learn 
you become aware of education don added when neneh was 
growing up we started visiting schools ourselves thats what 
education is not in material things or this false love the most 
important thing you can give kids is yourself 
don cherry born in 1936 grew up in the watts section of los 
angeles and was soon exposed to billie holliday charlie parker and 
other jazz legends like neneh music was more important than 
school and he began cutting classes for the chance to jam with 
local musicians 
he was just 17 when he started playing with coleman the alto 
sax player who helped develop free jazz which relied on 
spontaneous interaction between musicians rather than extended 
solos 
in the late 1950s cherry was part of the coleman quartet whose 
engagement at new yorks five spot cafe attracted worldwide 
attention 
he also played with sonny rollins and john coltrane and made his 
first visit to the third world in the mid60s going from 
copenhagen to morocco and soon incorporated new sounds into his 
music 
you look at the catalogs in the record stores he said 
the jazz department new wave fusion new age its all coming 
together its world music 
were growing as listeners and as players too weve become 
more aware of what we have to work with jazz has gotten to be a 
gumbo americas a gumbo its good to know about each others 
culture its one of the greatest forms of education and its 
happening in all of music 
for art deco he plays with just three other musicians all 
longtime friends tenor saxophonist james clay bassist charlie 
haden and drummer billy higgins 
they recorded 10 songs including three coleman numbers the 
blessing when will the blues leave and compute the 
standards body and soul and ive grown accustomed to your 
face and the title track a cherry composition 
it was a pleasure he said we had the best engineer in 
jazz rudy van gelder the producer john snyder had his heart in 
it and the musicians had been playing together we played at the 
village vanguard for one week and at the end of the week we started 
recording 
its a pure jazz record 
the cherrys talk excitedly about working together and recording 
each others material both see music as a way of communication 
music is good that way don said a lot of people dont 
handle music because it makes you compoletely nude you play music 
and you can find a whole persons innerself when youre creating 
and improvising you have to be real honest 
neneh spoke of her song manchild and how it expressed her 
idea of personal growth its about a man who feels inadequate 
feels he has to establish himself materially in a certain kind of 
way 
you see a lot of people aggressive people who are macho 
because theyre insecure im in touch with myself and im 
getting to know myself more 
