the currency advantage that once gave japanese firms an edge in 
exports is greatly reduced now so they must become even more 
efficient europe may become a vast common market in 1992 adding 
greatly to competitiveness there 
but its an old story in the united states there was little 
industrial fat to be found in american companies right after world 
war ii but the easy days of the 1960s took care of that waste and 
inefficiency developed 
by the 1970s american companies were finding themselves at a 
competitive disadvantage the industrial might of europe and japan 
destroyed in the war was much newer and more technologically 
efficient than american factories 
the effect was shocking the products of the bloated 
bureaucracies and dated factories of america were undercut by 
foreign products shipped thousands of miles to showrooms foreign 
quality steadily improved while americas fell 
that shocking experience brought on a crash diet old factories 
were closed layers of whitecollar workers were eliminated 
billions of dollars were spent on new production facilities 
nonessential units were sold off 
that desperate diet of the 1970s had much to do with the success 
of american business in the 1980s but success it seems has its 
dangers the worst of them complacency bureaucratic baggage has 
accreted again 
no company no matter how great its reputation is immune 
